External IPs 85.11.187.40 and 193.8.187.2 performed reconnaissance against FortiGate management interfaces by probing ports associated with MySQL (3306), web/application management (5001), Docker Remote API (2375/2376), and VNC remote desktop services (5900, 5902, 5904, 5905, 5910). The activity is consistent with automated service enumeration intended to identify exposed administrative services. All connection attempts were blocked by FortiGate Local-In Policies (traffic:local deny), no sessions were established, and no data was exchanged. Therefore, the observed activity had no impact on the environment and is assessed as unsuccessful reconnaissance.

Probable attacker intent

1. IP: 85.11.187.40
The objective of this IP appears to be identifying exposed database and application management services, specifically MySQL (3306) and admin portals (5001). This type of probing is typically performed to:

Detect weakly secured or exposed database services
Attempt credential brute-force attacks on MySQL
Exploit misconfigured web or admin interfaces
Gain initial access to internal applications for data extraction or lateral movement

2. IP: 193.8.187.2
This IP demonstrates broader infrastructure and remote access service enumeration, targeting Docker (2375/2376), VNC (5900–5910 range), and additional management/custom ports (4244). The likely objectives include:

Discovering exposed remote desktop (VNC) services for direct GUI access
Identifying Docker APIs that could allow container takeover and host compromise
Locating misconfigured internal services for remote code execution or persistence
Establishing a foothold for deeper network penetration or botnet recruitment
Overall interpretation

Both IPs are part of automated or semi-automated scanning infrastructure commonly used in early-stage attack chains. Their goal is not immediate exploitation, but discovery of vulnerable entry points that can be exploited in later attack phases such as brute force, exploitation, or credential theft.
